path = os.getcwd()+"\\Data"
dst=os.getcwd()+"\\Working"

def getRandomFile(path):
    randomDir = random.choice([(x) for x in list(os.scandir(path)) if x.is_dir()]).name
    randomFile = random.choice([f for f in list(os.scandir(path=path+"\\"+randomDir))]).name
    if os.path.isdir(path+"\\"+randomFile):
        print("Internal Directory")
        randomFile1 = random.choice([f for f in list(os.scandir(path=path+"\\"+randomDir+"\\"+randomFile))]).name
        print(randomFile1)
        return path+"\\"+randomDir+"\\"+randomFile+"\\"+randomFile1
    else:
        return path+"\\"+randomDir+"\\"+randomFile

for x in range(500):
    print(x)
    shutil.copy(getRandomFile(path),dst)

librosa.display.waveshow(x_, sr=sr_,ax=axis[1])

figure,axis = plt.subplots(4,figsize=(18,18))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8)
for i in range(4):
    x , sr = librosa.load(h[i])
    X = librosa.stft(x)

    Xdb = librosa.amplitude_to_db(abs(X))
    librosa.display.specshow(Xdb, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log',ax=axis[i])
plt.show()

figure,axis = plt.subplots(4,figsize=(18,18))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8)

for i in range(4):
    x , sr = librosa.load(h[i])
    zero_crossings = librosa.zero_crossings(x)
    print("Sum of zero crossing ", zero_crossings.sum())
    zcrs = librosa.feature.zero_crossing_rate(x)
    axis[i].plot(zcrs[0])
plt.show()

Sum of zero crossing  19321
Sum of zero crossing  17013
Sum of zero crossing  13771
Sum of zero crossing  14277

The zero-crossing rate (ZCR) is the rate at which a signal changes from positive to zero to negative or from negative to zero to positive.The signals are more sharp for happy sounds¶

In [13]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import minmax_scale
def normalize(x, axis=0):
    return minmax_scale(x, axis=axis)
In [14]:
figure,axis = plt.subplots(4,figsize=(18,18))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8)
plt.setp(axis, ylim=(-2,2))
plt.title('Spectral Centroids')
for i in range(4):
    x , sr = librosa.load(h[i])
    spectral_centroids = librosa.feature.spectral_centroid(x, sr=sr)[0]
    frames = range(len(spectral_centroids))
    t = librosa.frames_to_time(frames)
    librosa.display.waveshow(x, sr=sr, alpha=0.4,ax=axis[i])
    axis[i].plot(t, normalize(spectral_centroids), color='r')
plt.show()

Spectral centroid is a good predictor of the "brightness" of a sound. Happy sound signals seems more dominant¶

In [16]:
figure,axis = plt.subplots(4,figsize=(18,18))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8)
plt.setp(axis, ylim=(-2,2))
plt.title('Spectral Rolloff')
for i in range(4):
    x , sr = librosa.load(h[i])
    spectral_rolloff = librosa.feature.spectral_rolloff(x, sr=sr, roll_percent=0.01)[0]
    frames = range(len(spectral_rolloff))
    t = librosa.frames_to_time(frames)
    librosa.display.waveshow(x, sr=sr, alpha=0.4,ax=axis[i])
    axis[i].plot(t, normalize(spectral_rolloff), color='r')
plt.show()

Spectral rolloff is the frequency below which a specified percentage of the total spectral energy lies. We see highpass roll off in the read line and low pass roll off in the blue bars.¶

Mel scale is the scale of pitches that can be felt by the listener to be equal in distance from one another. We see more changes in colors when pitches in happy sound change.¶
